  {
    id: 6, title: "Imprecision", subtitle: "Nicht genügend Daten", xp: 150,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "dark", content: { title: "Imprecision", subtitle: "Der vierte Bereich: Haben wir genug? Daten?" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand why wide confidence intervals undermine certainty",
          "Apply the 'Optimal Information Size' concept",
          "Recognize when 95% CIs cross clinical decision thresholds",
          "Decide when to downgrade for imprecision"
        ],
        tip: "Statistical significance is not enough—confidence intervals must be clinically narrow."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Das PROWESS Mirage", title: "When 1,690 Deaths Weren't Enough",
        text: "In 2001, Eli Lilly's drotrecogin alfa (Xigris) was approved for severe sepsis based on the PROWESS trial. The trial showed <strong>6.1% absolute mortality reduction</strong>—from 30.8% to 24.7%. The FDA approved it despite concerns. Cost: $6,800 per treatment. Lilly projected billions in revenue.",
        followup: "Then came the confidence interval analysis. The 95% CI for mortality reduction ranged from <strong>1.9% to 10.4%</strong>. The benefit might be huge (10.4%) or clinically marginal (1.9%). With a drug this expensive and risky (increased bleeding), that uncertainty mattered. Subsequent trials failed to replicate PROWESS. The ADDRESS trial in less severe sepsis showed <strong>no benefit</strong>. The PROWESS-SHOCK trial confirmed <strong>no mortality benefit</strong> even in severe sepsis. In 2011, Lilly withdrew Xigris worldwide. A decade of use, billions spent, and the imprecision had warned us from the start."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📐", title: "Scenario: The Wide Confidence Interval",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A trial shows a new treatment reduces mortality from 20% to 14%—a 6% absolute reduction (RR 0.70, p=0.04). However, the 95% CI for absolute risk reduction is 0.5% to 11.5%. The lower bound (0.5%) is below your minimum clinically important difference of 2%.",
        question: "Sollten Sie wegen Ungenauigkeit herabstufen?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Nein – das Ergebnis ist statistisch signifikant", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "No—the point estimate shows clinically meaningful benefit", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Yes—the CI includes clinically unimportant effects", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Ja – das CI umfasst Schaden", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Statistische Signifikanz garantiert keine klinische Präzision. Wenn der tatsächliche Effekt nur 0,5 % betragen könnte (unter Ihrem minimalen wichtigen Unterschied), können Sie die Behandlung nicht mit gutem Gewissen empfehlen. GRADE erfordert eine Herabstufung, wenn die CIs klinische Entscheidungsschwellen überschreiten, nicht nur den Nullwert.",
          incorrect: "Die Untergrenze des CI (0,5 %) fällt unter die minimale klinisch wichtige Differenz (2 %). Dies bedeutet, dass die tatsächliche Wirkung möglicherweise zu gering ist, um die Behandlungskosten/-risiken zu rechtfertigen. Statistische Signifikanz reicht nicht aus – CIs müssen klinisch unwichtige Effekte ausschließen, um eine hohe Sicherheit zu gewährleisten."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Die optimale Informationsgröße", title: "Why Sample Size Matters for Certainty",
        text: "Consider a simple thought experiment: You flip a coin 4 times and get 3 heads (75%). Would you bet your house that the coin is biased? Now flip 1,000 times and get 750 heads. Same proportion—but utterly different certainty.",
        followup: "GRADE uses the <strong>Optimal Information Size (OIS)</strong> concept. This asks: 'How many events would a single adequately-powered trial need to reliably detect this effect?' If your meta-analysis has fewer events than the OIS, you're in the position of the person who flipped 4 coins—the proportion might be right, but you don't have enough data to be confident. For mortality outcomes, OIS is typically <strong>200-400 events</strong>. Many celebrated meta-analyses have far fewer."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔢", title: "Szenario: Die kleine Metaanalyse",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A meta-analysis of 8 RCTs (total n=1,200) shows a treatment prevents death with RR 0.65 (95% CI 0.45-0.95). The total number of deaths across all trials is 87. The pooled estimate is statistically significant. Your OIS calculation suggests 300 events would be needed.",
        question: "Sollten Sie wegen Ungenauigkeit herabstufen?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No—statistical significance means adequate precision", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "No—8 RCTs provide adequate power through meta-analysis", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Yes—87 events is well below the OIS of 300", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Nur wenn das CI kreuzt 1.0", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! 87 Ereignisse im Vergleich zu einem OIS von 300 bedeuten, dass wir über weniger als 30 % der benötigten Informationen verfügen. Die Schätzung mag richtig sein, aber wir befinden uns im Bereich der „kleinen Stichproben“, in dem zufällige Variationen dramatisch aussehende, aber unzuverlässige Effekte hervorrufen können. GRADE erfordert eine Herabstufung, wenn Ereignisse weit unter OIS liegen.",
          incorrect: "Meta-Analyse erzeugt keine Informationen auf magische Weise. 8 kleine Prüfungen mit insgesamt 87 Veranstaltungen entsprechen nicht einer großen Prüfung mit 300 Veranstaltungen. Die statistische Signifikanz ist wahrscheinlich fragil – ein paar Ereignisse würden die Schlussfolgerung ändern. OIS bietet eine Realitätsprüfung der Probenadäquanz."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Hydroxyethylstärke-Umkehrung", title: "When 10,000 Patients Weren't Enough... Then Were",
        text: "Hydroxyethyl starch (HES) fluids were used for decades in critically ill patients. Early meta-analyses with few events showed possible benefit. Then came the large trials: <strong>6S trial (798 patients)</strong>, <strong>CHEST trial (7,000 patients)</strong>, <strong>CRISTAL trial (2,857 patients)</strong>.",
        followup: "The large trials showed HES <strong>increased mortality and kidney failure</strong>. The earlier 'positive' evidence had been imprecise—confidence intervals that allowed for benefit also allowed for the substantial harm that large trials eventually detected. The European Medicines Agency suspended HES for critical illness. Imprecise evidence had allowed a harmful intervention to persist for years."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚠️", title: "Scenario: The Borderline Mortality Signal",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Eine Metaanalyse zeigt ein RR für den Tod von 1,25 (95 %-KI 0,98–1,60) bei einer Behandlung. Das Ergebnis tendiert zum Schaden, ist aber statistisch nicht signifikant. Ihre Leitlinie muss entscheiden, ob diese Behandlung für eine nicht tödliche Erkrankung empfohlen wird, für die es Alternativen gibt.",
        question: "How should imprecision affect your recommendation?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Die Behandlung ist sicher – CI umfasst 1,0", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "The treatment is harmful—point estimate shows 25% increase", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Erhebliche Unsicherheit hinsichtlich des Schadens – CI steht im Einklang mit einem Anstieg der Sterblichkeit um bis zu 60 %", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Need more trials before any conclusion", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The upper bound (1.60) represents a 60% mortality increase. For a non-fatal condition with alternatives, that possibility should drive decision-making. 'Not statistically significant' doesn't mean safe—it means we can't rule out substantial harm. GRADE incorporates the entire CI, not just p-values.",
          incorrect: "Die Obergrenze des CI von 1,60 bedeutet, dass wir Eine um 60 % erhöhte Sterblichkeit kann nicht ausgeschlossen werden. Bei einer Behandlung einer nicht tödlichen Erkrankung, für die es Alternativen gibt, sollte diese Ungewissheit über einen schwerwiegenden Schaden die Entscheidung dominieren. Statistische Nicht-Signifikanz ≠ Sicherheit."
        }
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Der Fragilitätsindex",
        subtitle: "How stable is statistical significance?",
        text: "The fragility index asks: 'How many patients would need to have had a different outcome to make this result non-significant?' A fragility index of 3 means if just 3 patients had different outcomes, the p-value would cross 0.05. Many published 'significant' findings have fragility indices under 10.",
        highlight: "Eine Studie mit einem Fragilitätsindex von 5 bedeutet, dass das „signifikante“ Ergebnis von weniger Patienten abhängt, als in Ihrem Büro-Wartezimmer sitzen."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Die Tranexamsäure Triumph", title: "When Precision Demanded 20,000 Patients",
        text: "Could tranexamic acid (TXA) reduce death from bleeding in trauma? Early trials were suggestive but imprecise. The <strong>CRASH-2 trial</strong> took a different approach: enroll enough patients to get a precise answer.",
        followup: "<strong>20,211 patients</strong> across 274 hospitals in 40 countries. Result: TXA reduced death from bleeding from 5.7% to 4.9%—a 0.8% absolute reduction. The 95% CI was <strong>0.3% to 1.3%</strong>. Finally, precision: the entire CI showed clinically meaningful benefit. The WHO added TXA to its Essential Medicines List. The precision wasn't just scientific—it changed global policy because decision-makers could trust the narrow bounds."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "✓", title: "Scenario: The Precise But Small Effect",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A mega-trial (n=40,000) shows a treatment reduces mortality with RR 0.95 (95% CI 0.91-0.99). The result is statistically significant and the CI is narrow. However, the absolute risk reduction is 0.3% (NNT = 333). Your minimum clinically important difference for this outcome is 0.2%.",
        question: "Sollten Sie wegen Ungenauigkeit herabstufen?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Yes—the effect is too small to matter clinically", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "No—the narrow CI excludes clinically unimportant effects", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Yes—NNT of 333 suggests imprecision", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot determine without knowing the OIS", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The entire CI (0.91-0.99) lies below 1.0, and the corresponding absolute effects (0.1%-0.5%) are all above your minimum important difference of 0.2%. Small but precise effects that meet the clinical threshold don't require downgrading for imprecision. The issue is clinical judgment about whether the effect justifies intervention.",
          incorrect: "Bei der Ungenauigkeit geht es um Konfidenzintervalle, nicht um die Effektgröße. Ein kleiner, aber genau abgeschätzter Effekt, der klinisch unwichtige Werte ausschließt, ist nicht ungenau – er ist nur gering. Ob eine absolute Reduzierung um 0,3 % eine Behandlung rechtfertigt, ist ein Werteurteil und keine Frage der Präzision."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die JUPITER-Kontroverse", title: "When 17,802 Patients Still Weren't Enough",
        text: "The JUPITER trial enrolled <strong>17,802 patients</strong> to test rosuvastatin for primary prevention. After just 1.9 years (planned: 5 years), it was stopped early for 'overwhelming benefit.' Heart attacks were reduced by 54%! Headlines celebrated. Rosuvastatin prescriptions soared.",
        followup: "But critics noticed problems. Only <strong>68 heart attacks</strong> total across both groups—fragility index of just 4. The wide confidence intervals (0.29-0.73) reflected genuine uncertainty. Early stopping inflates effect sizes by 30% on average. And absolute risk reduction was just <strong>0.35%</strong> over 1.9 years—NNT of 286. A 'landmark' trial with thousands of patients still had imprecision concerns because it was stopped before enough events accumulated. Large n doesn't guarantee precision when event rates are low."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⏹️", title: "Szenario: Der vorzeitig abgebrochene Prozess",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A large trial (n=10,000) is stopped early after 2 years (planned: 5) for 'overwhelming efficacy.' The treatment shows 50% relative risk reduction. However, only 45 total events occurred, and the original planned stopping boundary was crossed by just 2 events.",
        question: "How should early stopping affect certainty assessment?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No concern—large sample size ensures precision", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Herabstufung wegen Ungenauigkeit – frühes Anhalten verstärkt die Wirkung und erzeugt Fragilität Ergebnisse", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Upgrade certainty—stopping early proves the effect is large", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Neutral—monitoring rules are pre-specified", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Early stopping typically inflates effect sizes by 30%. With only 45 events and crossing the boundary by 2, this finding is extremely fragile. Large n doesn't help when event rates are low—you need enough events, not just patients. GRADE recommends downgrading for trials stopped early with few events.",
          incorrect: "Früh abgebrochene Studien überschätzen die Auswirkungen systematisch. Bei 45 Ereignissen und einem Fragilitätsindex von ~2 würde die Reduzierung um 50 % verschwinden, wenn nur zwei Patienten unterschiedliche Ergebnisse hätten. Die große Stichprobe ist irrelevant – es sind Ereignisse, die die Präzision vorantreiben."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Die ISIS-4-Lektion", title: "Als 58.000 Patienten die Frage beantworteten",
        text: "After GISSI-2 suggested magnesium might reduce mortality in heart attack patients, smaller trials showed inconsistent results. The <strong>ISIS-4</strong> trial was designed to end the debate: <strong>58,050 patients</strong>, the largest heart attack trial ever. If magnesium worked, this trial would prove it.",
        followup: "Result: magnesium showed <strong>no benefit</strong> (mortality 7.64% vs. 7.24%, NS). The pooled meta-analysis before ISIS-4 had shown significant benefit—but was driven by small trials with imprecise estimates. When finally tested with adequate precision, the effect vanished. This pattern—dramatic effects in small trials, null effects in large trials—is so common it has a name: 'the winner's curse.' Small trials select for extreme results; large trials reveal reality."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🎲", title: "Scenario: Small Trial Meta-Analysis vs. Large Trial",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A meta-analysis of 15 small trials (total n=2,000, 180 events) shows significant mortality benefit (RR 0.65, p=0.001). A single large trial (n=15,000, 2,100 events) shows no benefit (RR 0.98, p=0.61). The meta-analysis was published first.",
        question: "Wie sollten Sie diese widersprüchlichen Ergebnisse gewichten?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Average them—more trials means more evidence", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Prefer the meta-analysis—15 trials beat 1 trial", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Bevorzugen Sie die große Studie – sie hat 10x mehr Ereignisse und Präzision", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Beweise für nicht schlüssig erklären", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! 2.100 Ereignisse im Vergleich zu 180 Ereignissen bedeuten, dass die große Studie etwa 12-mal mehr Informationen enthält. Metaanalysen kleiner Studien sind anfällig für Publikationsbias und den Fluch des Gewinners. Wenn eine große, ausreichend aussagekräftige Studie im Widerspruch zu Metaanalysen kleiner Studien steht, bringt die große Studie normalerweise die Wahrheit ans Licht.",
          incorrect: "ISIS-4 taught this lesson. Small trials showed magnesium benefit; the 58,000-patient trial showed nothing. Events determine precision, not number of trials. Publication bias and random variation create false signals in small trial meta-analyses that large trials correct."
        }
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Imprecision Assessment Checklist",
        items: [
          "Does the 95% CI cross clinically important thresholds?",
          "Kreuzt das CI sowohl Nutzen als auch Schaden?",
          "Liegt die Gesamtzahl der Ereignisse unter der optimalen Informationsgröße?",
          "Was ist der Fragilitätsindex für Schlüsselergebnisse?",
          "Would the upper or lower bound change clinical decision-making?"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "Why does GRADE require downgrading when confidence intervals cross 'clinical decision thresholds' even if statistically significant?",
        options: [
          { text: "Statistische Konventionen sind willkürlich", correct: false },
          { text: "The true effect might be too small (or too harmful) to justify treatment", correct: true },
          { text: "P-values don't account for sample size", correct: false },
          { text: "Confidence intervals are more accurate than p-values", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Wenn eine Behandlung die Sterblichkeit „erheblich“ senkt, das KI jedoch zu geringe Auswirkungen aufweist, um die Kosten/das Risiko zu rechtfertigen – oder erhebliche Schäden mit sich bringt – können wir sie nicht mit gutem Gewissen empfehlen. GRADE beurteilt die Präzision anhand klinischer Schwellenwerte und nicht anhand statistischer Konventionen.",
          incorrect: "Klinische Entscheidungen erfordern die Kenntnis, ob der tatsächliche Effekt groß genug ist, um von Bedeutung zu sein. Ein statistisch signifikantes Ergebnis mit einem KI-Bereich von „geringfügig hilfreich“ bis „erheblich schädlich“ gibt keinen Hinweis auf die Behandlung. GRADE verwendet klinische Schwellenwerte, weil diese Entscheidungen erfordern."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 7, title: "Publication Bias", subtitle: "Die unsichtbaren Beweise", xp: 160,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "red-bg", content: { title: "Publication Bias", subtitle: "Der fünfte Bereich: Welche Beweise haben uns nie erreicht?" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Verstehen Sie, wie negative Studien aus der Literatur verschwinden",
          "Interpret funnel plots and their limitations",
          "Recognize when publication bias likely distorts evidence",
          "Decide when to downgrade certainty for publication bias"
        ],
        tip: "Die gefährlichsten Beweise sind Beweise, die Sie nie erhalten siehe."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Paroxetin-Täuschung", title: "GlaxoSmithKline's Hidden Children",
        text: "In the early 2000s, GSK marketed paroxetine (Paxil) for adolescent depression. The published evidence looked convincing. Study 329, published in the <em>Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry</em>, reported paroxetine was <strong>'generally well tolerated and effective.'</strong> Thousands of teenagers were prescribed the drug.",
        followup: "Then lawsuits forced GSK to release internal documents. Study 329 had actually shown paroxetine was <strong>no better than placebo</strong> and increased suicidal behavior. GSK had conducted other trials—also negative—that were never published. The published paper had been ghost-written by a medical communications company. When all studies were combined, the truth emerged: paroxetine didn't work for teen depression and was dangerous. The published literature had been systematically manipulated. Publication bias wasn't passive—it was manufactured."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
